          "name_local": "พระบรมมหาราชวัง",
          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "The Grand Palace is Bangkok's most iconic landmark—a sprawling complex of buildings that served as the royal residence from 1782 until 1925. Within its walls sits Wat Phra Kaew (Temple of the Emerald Buddha), Thailand's most sacred temple housing a 15th-century jade Buddha statue. The architecture is a dazzling display of golden spires, intricate mosaics, and mythological guardians. It's touristy but essential for understanding Thai cultural identity.",
            "vibe": "Opulent, Sacred, Crowded",
            "history": "King Rama I founded the Grand Palace in 1782 when he moved the capital from Thonburi to Bangkok. It was modeled on the former capital Ayutthaya's palace. For 150 years, it was the administrative and royal residence center. The Emerald Buddha was captured from Laos in 1778 and became the palladium of Thailand—a protective talisman for the kingdom. After King Rama V built the European-style Dusit Palace in the early 1900s, the Grand Palace gradually became ceremonial rather than residential.",
            "insider_tip": "Arrive at 8:30 AM when gates open to beat the tour bus crowds. Dress code is strictly enforced—shoulders and knees covered, no sandals. Sarongs and shirts are available for rent if needed. The Emerald Buddha temple is the main highlight; the palace buildings are only viewable from outside. Audio guides are worth it for understanding the symbolism. Avoid weekends and Thai holidays.",
            "price_level": "Expensive",
            "good_for": ["First-time visitors", "History buffs", "Photography"],
            "duration": "2-3 hours",
            "best_time": "8:30 AM (opening time)"
          },
          "image": "/images/bangkok/grand-palace.jpg",
          "geo": { "lat": 13.7500, "lng": 100.4915 }
