          "slug": "wat-arun",
          "name_en": "Wat Arun",
          "name_local": "วัดอรุณ",
          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "Wat Arun (Temple of Dawn) is a Khmer-style Buddhist temple on the Thonburi side of the Chao Phraya River, famous for its 70-meter central prang (tower) covered in colorful porcelain and seashells. The tower is steep and climbable, offering views over the river. At sunset, the temple glows golden—though ironically, it's more photogenic from across the river at sunrise when the first light hits it.",
            "vibe": "Majestic, Riverside, Architectural",
            "history": "Wat Arun dates to the Ayutthaya period but was renovated and enlarged during King Rama II's reign (early 19th century). The central prang represents Mount Meru, the center of the universe in Buddhist cosmology. The colorful decorations are broken Chinese porcelain—ballast from trading ships repurposed as art. It was briefly home to the Emerald Buddha before it moved to the Grand Palace. The temple's name comes from Aruna, the Hindu god of dawn.",
            "insider_tip": "The stairs up the central prang are extremely steep (almost 70-degree angle)—not for those with vertigo or mobility issues. Go late afternoon (4-5 PM) when the heat subsides but before sunset crowds arrive. The best photos are actually from across the river at Tha Tien Pier or from rooftop bars in the Old City. Cross by ferry (4 Baht) rather than taxi to avoid the traffic nightmare.",
            "price_level": "Affordable",
            "good_for": ["Photography", "Architecture lovers", "River views"],
            "duration": "1-1.5 hours",
            "best_time": "Late afternoon (4-5 PM)"
          },
          "image": "/images/bangkok/wat-arun.jpg",
          "geo": { "lat": 13.7437, "lng": 100.4887 }
        },
        {
          "id": "temp-003",
          "slug": "wat-pho",
          "name_en": "Wat Pho",
          "name_local": "วัดโพธิ์",
          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "Wat Pho is Bangkok's largest and oldest temple, home to the massive 46-meter-long Reclining Buddha covered in gold leaf. Beyond the famous statue, the temple complex contains over 1,000 Buddha images, beautiful murals, and is considered the birthplace of traditional Thai massage—a massage school still operates on-site. It's less crowded and more peaceful than the Grand Palace despite being next door.",
            "vibe": "Serene, Historic, Authentic",
            "history": "Wat Pho was founded in the 16th century during the Ayutthaya period but was extensively renovated by King Rama I in the late 1700s. King Rama III transformed it into Thailand's first public university in the 1830s, with medical and massage knowledge inscribed on stone tablets throughout the complex. The Reclining Buddha was added in 1832, depicting Buddha's entry into nirvana. The temple was designated a UNESCO site as it houses the largest collection of Buddha images in Thailand.",
            "insider_tip": "Visit Wat Pho before or after the Grand Palace since they're walking distance apart—but Wat Pho is calmer and less overwhelming. The traditional Thai massage school offers 30-minute sessions (cheap and authentic). Remove shoes before entering all temple buildings. Walk beyond the Reclining Buddha to explore the quieter courtyards and pavilions. Early morning (8-9 AM) or late afternoon (4-5 PM) are best to avoid midday heat.",
            "price_level": "Affordable",
            "good_for": ["Culture enthusiasts", "Photography", "Massage"],
            "duration": "1.5-2 hours",
            "best_time": "Early morning or late afternoon"
          },
          "image": "/images/bangkok/wat-pho.jpg",
          "geo": { "lat": 13.7465, "lng": 100.4927 }
        },
        {
