          "slug": "chao-phraya-boat",
          "name_en": "Chao Phraya Express Boat",
          "name_local": "เรือด่วนเจ้าพระยา",
          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "The Chao Phraya Express Boat is Bangkok's river bus system—wooden commuter boats that zip up and down the river stopping at piers along the way. The Orange Flag boats are the local workhorse (cheap, frequent, no air-con), while tourist boats are overpriced gimmicks. This is authentic Bangkok transit—crowded, breezy, and offering views of temples, palaces, and riverside life impossible to see from land.",
            "vibe": "Authentic, Scenic, Practical",
            "history": "River transport has been Bangkok's lifeblood since its founding—the city was called the 'Venice of the East' when canals were the primary roads. The modern express boat service began in the 1970s as traffic congestion worsened. The iconic wooden boats with canvas roofs became symbols of Bangkok. While most canals have been paved over for roads, the Chao Phraya remains a functioning commuter artery, carrying over 50,000 passengers daily.",
            "insider_tip": "Buy a day pass (180 Baht) for unlimited Orange Flag boat rides—it pays for itself after 3-4 trips. Avoid the Blue Flag tourist boat (triple the price). Sit outside on the back or sides for breeze and photos. Key stops: Tha Tien (Wat Pho/Wat Arun), Ratchawong (Chinatown), Sathorn (for Skytrain connection). Boats get packed during rush hours (7-9 AM, 5-7 PM). Have exact change ready—conductors move fast.",
            "price_level": "Affordable",
            "good_for": ["Everyone", "River views", "Commuting"],
            "duration": "Varies (20 min-2 hours)",
            "best_time": "Late afternoon (4-6 PM)"
          },
          "image": "/images/bangkok/river-boat.jpg",
