          "slug": "yaowarat-night-food",
          "name_en": "Yaowarat Night Food Walk",
          "name_local": "เยาวราช",
          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "Yaowarat Road in Chinatown transforms after sunset into Bangkok's most spectacular street food scene—neon-lit chaos with hundreds of stalls selling seafood, noodles, dim sum, and desserts. The street itself becomes a dining room with plastic tables and stools. The energy is electric, the smells overwhelming, and the food is some of Bangkok's best. This is essential Bangkok—not a tourist attraction, but living culture.",
            "vibe": "Chaotic, Electric, Delicious",
            "history": "Yaowarat was established in 1891 under King Rama V as Bangkok's Chinatown when the Chinese community was relocated from Rattanakosin to make way for the Grand Palace expansion. The Teochew Chinese dominated trade and commerce, making Yaowarat the economic heart of Bangkok. The street food culture emerged as workers needed cheap meals, evolving into the epic night market by the 1970s-80s. Today, it's protected as cultural heritage.",
            "insider_tip": "Go after 7 PM when the street comes alive—earlier and it's just traffic. Start at Odeon Circle and walk the length of Yaowarat Road. Must-tries: crab fried rice at Jay Fai area, oyster omelet (hoy tod), bird's nest soup stalls. Bring cash—nowhere takes cards. The side alleys (Soi Texas, Soi Plaeng Nam) have the best hidden gems. Weekend nights are insane—go weekday if possible.",
            "price_level": "Moderate",
            "good_for": ["Foodies", "Night owls", "Street food lovers"],
            "duration": "2-3 hours",
            "best_time": "7 PM-midnight"
          },
          "image": "/images/bangkok/chinatown.jpg",
          "geo": { "lat": 13.7410, "lng": 100.5085 }
        },
        {
          "id": "act-003",
          "slug": "thai-massage-local",
          "name_en": "Traditional Thai Massage",
          "name_local": "นวดแผนไทย",
          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "Traditional Thai massage (nuad phaen Thai) is a 2,000-year-old healing practice involving stretching, acupressure, and assisted yoga poses. Unlike Swedish massage, you stay clothed in loose pajamas while the therapist uses hands, elbows, knees, and feet to manipulate your body. It can be intense—sometimes painful—but leaves you feeling realigned. This is daily health maintenance for locals, not a luxury spa treatment.",
            "vibe": "Therapeutic, Intense, Traditional",
            "history": "Thai massage has roots in Indian Ayurvedic medicine and Chinese acupressure, brought to Thailand by Buddhist monks over 2,000 years ago. Wat Pho became the center for codifying and teaching the practice. Massage was part of traditional medicine, treating ailments through pressure points ('sen' energy lines). In the 20th century, commercial massage shops proliferated as tourism grew. In 2019, UNESCO recognized Thai massage as Intangible Cultural Heritage.",
            "insider_tip": "Avoid tourist trap spas near Khao San or Sukhumvit—they're overpriced and mediocre. Go to the Wat Pho Traditional Thai Massage School for authentic, affordable sessions (500-600 Baht for 2 hours). Alternatively, find local shops in residential neighborhoods where prices are 300-400 Baht. Communicate if pressure is too much—'bao bao' means gentle. Don't eat a heavy meal before; stretching on a full stomach is uncomfortable.",
            "price_level": "Affordable",
            "good_for": ["Relaxation", "Cultural experience", "Everyone"],
            "duration": "1-2 hours",
            "best_time": "Afternoon"
          },
          "image": "/images/bangkok/massage.jpg",
          "geo": { "lat": 13.7465, "lng": 100.4927 }
        },
        {
          "id": "act-004",
          "slug": "lumpini-park",
          "name_en": "Lumpini Park",
          "name_local": "สวนลุมพินี",
          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "Lumpini Park is Bangkok's largest and most famous green space—120 acres of lakes, paths, and open lawns in the heart of the business district. At dawn, locals practice Tai Chi, jog, and feed the massive monitor lizards that roam freely. At sunset, outdoor aerobics classes blast music while hundreds exercise in sync. It's Bangkok's communal living room—where the city breathes.",
            "vibe": "Green, Communal, Peaceful",
            "history": "King Rama VI donated the land and opened Lumpini Park in the 1920s, naming it after Buddha's birthplace in Nepal. It was Bangkok's first public park, part of modernization efforts copying European cities. During WWII, it was used for military training. By the 1980s-90s, it became the city's exercise hub. The monitor lizards arrived naturally from nearby canals and now number in the hundreds—protected and fed by visitors.",
            "insider_tip": "Go at 6-7 AM to see morning Tai Chi, traditional Chinese exercise groups, and the most active wildlife (monitor lizards sunbathe near the lake). At 6 PM, witness the outdoor aerobics phenomenon—hundreds of people dancing in unison to pounding music. Paddle boats are available on the lake (cheap, relaxing). The park is safe day and night. Watch for monitor lizards on paths—they're harmless but can be startling when large (2 meters).",
            "price_level": "Affordable",
            "good_for": ["Morning exercise", "Wildlife", "Relaxation"],
            "duration": "1-2 hours",
            "best_time": "6-7 AM or 6 PM"
          },
          "image": "/images/bangkok/lumpini.jpg",
          "geo": { "lat": 13.7314, "lng": 100.5417 }
        },
        {
          "id": "act-005",
          "slug": "muay-thai",
          "name_en": "Muay Thai Boxing",
          "name_local": "มวยไทย",
          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "Muay Thai is Thailand's national sport—an 8-point striking martial art using fists, elbows, knees, and shins. Watching a live fight at Rajadamnern or Lumpinee Stadium means experiencing the ritualistic wai kru dance, the hypnotic traditional music, the roaring crowd, and the violent beauty of the combat. This isn't a tourist show; it's real fighting with betting, blood, and cultural significance.",
            "vibe": "Intense, Traditional, Visceral",
            "history": "Muay Thai evolved from ancient Siamese battlefield combat techniques, formalized as a sport in the 16th century. It was entertainment for royalty and commoners alike. Modern rules were codified in the 1920s, adopting Western boxing elements like gloves and rounds. For centuries, Muay Thai was both martial art and gambling vehicle—betting is integral to the experience. Lumpinee and Rajadamnern stadiums opened in the 1950s-60s and remain the sport's temples.",
            "insider_tip": "Rajadamnern Stadium has fights on Mondays, Wednesdays, Thursdays, and Sundays; Lumpinee on Tuesdays, Fridays, and Saturdays. Ringside seats are expensive (2,000+ Baht) but immersive; third-class seats are cheaper and still atmospheric. The earlier fights feature younger/amateur fighters; main events are later (9-10 PM). Watch the betting signals in the crowd—it's a parallel show. Don't go to tourist 'Muay Thai dinner shows'—they're watered-down performances.",
            "price_level": "Moderate",
            "good_for": ["Sports fans", "Cultural experience", "Evening activity"],
            "duration": "3-4 hours",
            "best_time": "Evening (6-10 PM)"
          },
          "image": "/images/bangkok/muay-thai.jpg",
          "geo": { "lat": 13.7600, "lng": 100.5090 }
        },
        {
