          "slug": "listening-bars",
          "name_en": "Audiophile Listening Bars",
          "name_local": "Vinyl Bars",
          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "Bangkok's listening bar scene is a sophisticated alternative to loud clubs—intimate venues with audiophile-grade sound systems, extensive vinyl collections (especially Thai Molam, Luk Thung, and jazz), and craft cocktails. The ethos is respectful silence during songs, deep listening, and music appreciation. Venues like Studio Lam, Alonetogether, and Badmotel attract Bangkok's creative class seeking sonic refuge.",
            "vibe": "Intimate, Sonic, Sophisticated",
            "history": "The listening bar concept came from Japan's 'jazz kissa' culture but adapted to Bangkok in the 2010s as young Thais rediscovered vintage Thai music—particularly Molam (Isaan folk) and Luk Thung (country). Audiophiles invested in high-end analog systems to share their collections. These bars became cultural spaces celebrating Thai musical heritage alongside Western classics. They represent Bangkok's creative renaissance and rejection of mindless nightlife.",
            "insider_tip": "Studio Lam in Ari is the pioneer—specializes in Thai Molam and Luk Thung with an incredible sound system. Alonetogether near Chulalongkorn University focuses on jazz and soul. Most have a cover charge (200-300 Baht) including one drink. Respect the 'no talking during songs' rule. Ask the DJ/owner for recommendations—they're passionate educators. Many only open 8 PM onwards and are closed Mondays-Wednesdays.",
            "price_level": "Moderate",
            "good_for": ["Music lovers", "Date night", "Evening activity"],
            "duration": "2-3 hours",
            "best_time": "9 PM-midnight"
