        {
          "id": "nat-001",
          "slug": "bang-krachao",
          "name_en": "Bang Krachao (Green Lung)",
          "name_local": "บางกระเจ้า",
          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "Bang Krachao is a 12-square-kilometer jungle island in a bend of the Chao Phraya River, nicknamed Bangkok's 'Green Lung.' It's agricultural land, mangrove forests, and villages connected by elevated concrete bike paths. Despite being in central Bangkok, it feels rural—wooden houses, fruit orchards, monitor lizards, and silence. Rent a bike and ride the network of paths through green tunnels—a total escape from concrete chaos.",
            "vibe": "Rural, Peaceful, Green",
            "history": "Bang Krachao remained undeveloped because it's on the flood-prone west bank and protected by geography—the river loops create a natural moat. In the 1990s-2000s, developers eyed it for housing, but environmental groups campaigned to preserve it as Bangkok's 'lung.' The elevated bike paths were built in the 2000s to promote ecotourism. It represents what Bangkok was before urbanization—an agricultural delta with canals and villages.",
            "insider_tip": "Take a ferry from Klong Toei Pier (40 Baht) to Bang Krachao—it's a 5-minute crossing. Rent a bike immediately upon arrival (50-100 Baht for the day). The Bang Nampheung Floating Market (weekends only) is touristy but fine for lunch. The real charm is cycling the quiet paths through jungle. Go on weekdays to avoid crowds. Bring water, sunscreen, and mosquito repellent. It's hot and humid—go early morning (8-11 AM) or late afternoon.",
            "price_level": "Affordable",
