          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "Chatuchak is one of the world's largest weekend markets—15,000 stalls across 35 acres selling everything from vintage clothes and antiques to live animals, plants, and street food. It's organized into numbered sections but still feels like a maze. The heat, crowds, and sensory overload are intense, but it's essential Bangkok—where locals shop for bargains and unique finds.",
            "vibe": "Massive, Chaotic, Treasure-hunt",
            "history": "Chatuchak started in 1942 as a government initiative to provide affordable goods post-WWII. It moved to its current location in 1982. What began as farmers selling produce evolved into a mega-market as Bangkok's economy grew. By the 1990s-2000s, it became a tourist attraction while remaining authentically local. It's now a Bangkok institution—families come to shop, eat, and spend entire Saturdays navigating its sections.",
            "insider_tip": "Go early (9-10 AM) before the midday heat becomes unbearable—afternoons are brutal. Wear light clothes, comfortable shoes, and bring water. The market has numbered sections: Section 2-3 for clothes, Section 7-8 for vintage, Section 26-27 for home decor. Bargain hard—starting price is often 30-40% inflated. Eat at the interior food courts (cheaper than edge stalls). An afternoon visit means fewer crowds but punishing heat.",
            "price_level": "Moderate",
