          "description": {
            "short": "Bangkok's night markets are evening gathering places with food stalls, bars, live music, and shopping. Jodd Fairs (near Rama IX) is the current hot spot—a sprawling open-air market with hundreds of food vendors, craft beer bars, and a festival atmosphere. Unlike tourist traps, these markets are where young Bangkok locals hang out, eat, drink, and socialize.",
            "vibe": "Lively, Social, Contemporary",
            "history": "Night markets have existed in Bangkok since its founding, but the modern iteration—entertainment-focused rather than just commerce—emerged in the 2010s. Markets like Rot Fai (Train Market) and later Jodd Fairs pioneered the formula: Instagram-worthy food, craft beer, vintage aesthetics, and live music. They became date night destinations for young middle-class Thais. The trend reflects Bangkok's growing creative economy and youth culture.",
            "insider_tip": "Jodd Fairs is near Rama IX MRT—open Thursday-Sunday, 5 PM-midnight. Arrive around 6-7 PM when it's filling up but not packed. Food is reasonably priced (80-200 Baht per dish). Try the craft beer bars at the back. The scene peaks around 8-9 PM. Other good options: Talad Neon Pratunam (neon-lit Instagram heaven) and the weekend Train Market. These markets are about atmosphere as much as food—plan to hang out, not rush through.",
