            "history": "Pak Khlong Talat has operated since King Rama I's era (late 1700s) when it was a major produce and goods landing—'pak khlong' means 'mouth of the canal.' Flowers became the specialty in the early 20th century as Bangkok's middle class grew and Buddhist offerings created steady demand. The market runs 24 hours because temple ceremonies and events require fresh flowers at all hours. It survived multiple relocation attempts and remains in its original spot.",
            "insider_tip": "Visit between midnight and 5 AM for the most dramatic scene—trucks unloading, vendors arranging mountains of flowers, and the magical lighting. Alternatively, go at dawn (6-7 AM) to see the buying frenzy. Bring a camera—the visual overload is incredible. You can buy flowers dirt cheap (wholesale prices). The adjacent produce market is also worth exploring. Be careful walking—wet floors, fast-moving carts, and chaotic energy.",
