          "category": "sight",
          "is_generic_staple": false,
          "description": {
            "short": "Bangkok's rooftop bar scene offers spectacular sunset views from 40-60 floors up—the city sprawling below, rivers of traffic, and temple spires glowing golden. Venues like Octave, Vertigo, and Sky Bar (from The Hangover 2) serve expensive cocktails in glamorous settings. It's touristy and pricey, but the views are genuinely spectacular and the experience is quintessentially Bangkok.",
            "vibe": "Glamorous, Expensive, Panoramic",
            "history": "Bangkok's rooftop bar boom began in the 2000s as the skyline reached new heights. Sirocco's Sky Bar, opened in 2003, pioneered the concept—featured in The Hangover Part II, it became a global symbol of Bangkok nightlife. As luxury hotels proliferated, rooftop bars became competitive amenities. They cater to affluent locals, expats, and tourists willing to pay 500+ Baht per cocktail for the view. They represent Bangkok's transformation from low-rise chaos to vertical metropolis.",
            "insider_tip": "Most rooftop bars enforce dress codes (no flip-flops, shorts, or tank tops). Go at sunset (around 6 PM) to watch the city transition from day to night—arrive 30 minutes early to secure a good spot. Drinks are expensive (400-600 Baht per cocktail) but you're paying for the view. Octave at Marriott Sukhumvit is less touristy than Sky Bar and has 360-degree views. Tichuca at T-One building is newer and less crowded. Book ahead on weekends.",
